                                                                            1
EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
The Summer Internship Project (SIP) focused on conducting market research for the ranking of top B-Schools in India, with the objective of compiling, cleaning, validating, and organizing institutional data to support the 2025 rankings publication. The project involved systematic secondary research, outreach to institutions, and structured data management over an eight-week period.
In the initial phase, data was compiled from over 100 institutions based on previous year’s rankings. Information was manually gathered from emails, brochures, and official websites, and entered into pre-formatted Excel templates, forming the foundation of the database.
The second phase emphasized data cleaning and standardization. Duplicates and outliers were removed, fields such as fee structures, accreditations, and course names were standardized, and Excel formulas were used to ensure consistency. This created a reliable dataset for further evaluation.
Subsequent weeks focused on data enrichment and validation. Missing inputs were filled by directly contacting institutions, supplementing responses with verified public data such as infrastructure details, faculty size, and international collaborations. Independent verification improved the accuracy and credibility of the dataset.
Where institutions were unresponsive, follow-ups via calls and emails were conducted, recovering critical information on programs, placements, and batch strength. Fresh responses from over 30 institutions significantly improved the dataset’s completeness and recency.
The final stage of the internship involved structuring the validated data in alignment with the ranking methodology. Institutions were categorized, individual profiles were prepared, and index sheets were created for seamless navigation. The dataset was formatted with filters, color codes, and explanatory notes, ensuring usability for both editorial and analytics teams.
By the conclusion of the internship, a comprehensive and credible dataset was delivered, serving as a direct input for the 2025 B-School Rankings. Additionally, an executive summary of patterns and insights was prepared for senior editors, highlighting trends and data completeness across institutions.
This project enhanced skills in secondary research, data validation, Excel-based data management, institutional communication, and market analysis. It provided valuable 
                                                                                      2
exposure to the processes involved in preparing credible, large-scale educational rankings, contributing to both academic learning and practical research experience.


LEARNING FROM SIP

During the course of my Summer Internship Project, I gained extensive exposure to market research processes, institutional communication, and data management practices while contributing to the preparation of B-School rankings in India. The experience provided me with both technical and interpersonal learnings that are highly relevant to academic research and corporate projects.
One of the key learnings was developing professional communication skills while reaching out to institutions. I learned how to draft clear, concise, and respectful messages through emails and calls, manage responses, and conduct polite follow-ups. This enhanced my interpersonal and stakeholder management skills in an academic data setting.
I strengthened my ability to collect, review, and verify real-time data from multiple sources such as institutional websites, brochures, emails, and accreditation databases. I learned how to differentiate between credible information and promotional content, cross-check institutional claims, and maintain structured logs to cite sources and validate secondary data.
From a technical perspective, I developed proficiency in Excel-based data handling. This included manual recording of raw information, data cleaning techniques using functions like =TRIM(), =CLEAN(), and =PROPER(), handling missing values, removing duplicates, and ensuring standardized entries. I also practiced creating pivot tables, charts, and graphs to visualize trends and summarize large datasets, which improved my ability to translate raw data into actionable insights.
I also learned how to organize and categorize data meaningfully, segmenting institutions by zone, type, and specialization. I practiced incorporating new evaluation parameters into datasets for a more holistic assessment. These practices improved my attention to detail, accuracy, and ability to identify patterns such as ROI trends and accreditation distribution across institutions.

                                                                                   3
The project taught me persistence in data recovery and follow-ups, especially when institutions were unresponsive. I learned to creatively use alternative sources like archived reports and public databases while balancing deadlines by prioritizing essential information.
Finally, I gained experience in structured reporting and presentation. I learned how to prepare professional Excel-based databases with filters, legends, and notes for clarity, and how to create executive summaries that highlighted key findings. By presenting final deliverables to senior editors, I understood the role of interns in the publication cycle of reputed media houses, linking academic research with real-world outcomes.
Overall, this internship significantly enhanced my research, analytical, communication, and reporting skills, while giving me valuable exposure to the challenges and processes involved in large-scale educational rankings.















